			section
				h2.bullet Web of Trust basics
				h3.bullet The Web of Trust is something we use in PGP
				h3.bullet Essentially, it's a way to distribute and authenticate keys.
				h3.bullet Put another way, the Web of Trust allows you to retrieve and verify someone else's identity.

			section
				h2.bullet Keysigning
				h3.bullet Keysigning: the act of creating a digital signature of someone else's key
				h3.bullet You want to sign people's keys, to verify others' keys
				h3.bullet You want others to sign your keys, so others can verify your key
				h3.bullet Unless you have a problem with the government knowing your social graph.

			section
				h2.bullet A small note on how well you need to know the person
				h3.bullet You do not need to know a person at all to sign their key.
				h3.bullet You can even sign the key of a person you've just met. And, in fact, many people do at keysigning parties.
				h3.bullet Just be aware of how you need to verify their identity.

			section
				h2.bullet Keysigning best practices: for people you <em>do</em> know
				h3.bullet This is the easy part.
				h3.bullet A phone call will suffice. This is because you will recognize their voice - no (regular) texting!
				h3.bullet You can skip the phone call if you have already established a secure conversation with them in some other way.
				h3.bullet For example, if you've verified their identify over OTR, you can use OTR to send them your key.

			section
				h2.bullet Keysigning best practices: for people you <em>don't</em> know
				h3.bullet This isn't nearly as convenient. :(
				h3.bullet At <strong>minimum</strong> you must require at least one form of government-issued photo identification. A drivers license will work, as well as a passport.
				h3.bullet Compare photo ID to them, and compare the name on the ID to the name on the key
				h3.bullet If possible, send your signature to them instead of uploading it.
				h3.bullet (If you're using GNU/Linux, you can use caff.)

			section
				h2.bullet Creating a key
				h3.bullet The defaults are good
				h3.bullet <a href="https://www.debian-administration.org/users/dkg/weblog/97">Don't enter anything in the Comment field</a>
				h3.bullet Generate a revocation certificate
				h3.bullet Back up your key and your revocation certificate
				h3.bullet Never, ever give your key to any person or company, even if it has a password. If a website asks you to upload your key, be suspicious.

			section
				h2.bullet Getting GPG
				h3.bullet For Windows, get <a href="http://www.gpg4win.org/">Gpg4Win</a>
				h3.bullet For Mac OS X, get <a href="https://gpgtools.org/">GpgTools</a>
				h3.bullet For pretty much everything on GNU/Linux, you want to use GNOME Keyring. This is probably already installed; if not, use your package manager's software installation tool to install it.
				h3.bullet For KDE/Trinity, use either Kleopatra or KGpg.

			section
				h2.bullet Using GPG
				h3.bullet If you use your Mac's builtin Mail application, then GpgTools has provided a plugin for using GPG.
				h3.bullet For pretty much everyone else, I recommend using <a href="https://www.mozilla.org/en-US/thunderbird/">Mozilla Thunderbird</a> with <a href="https://www.enigmail.net/home/index.php">Enigmail</a>.
				h3.bullet For some GNU/Linux systems, Thunderbird may be called Icedove. It works the exact same way.

